# Done Checklist

Before declaring any non-trivial task complete, verify ALL of the following:

## Standard Checks

- [ ] Run: unit tests + lint + typecheck (project standard commands)
- [ ] Confirm: no unused imports, no dead code paths introduced
- [ ] Confirm: error handling and logging for new code branches
- [ ] Update `tasks/todo.md` — move completed items with date stamp, keep audit trail
- [ ] Update memory: write detail to `memory/topics/*.md`, then add ~150-char pointer to `MEMORY.md` (or use `python scripts/memory/memory_classify.py "entry"`)
- [ ] Sync long-term memory: run `python scripts/memory/extract-sessions.py --incremental` and `python scripts/memory/build-index.py --skip-embeddings`
- [ ] If MEMORY.md pointers exceed 50: run `python scripts/memory/attention_decay.py --apply`
- [ ] If user corrected you: update `tasks/lessons.md` with pattern + prevention rule
- [ ] Provide: short summary + files changed + commands run + results

## Definition of Done (DoD) Template

For non-trivial tasks, define completion criteria BEFORE starting work using three categories:

1. **Functional criteria** — what the code must DO (observable behavior, not implementation details)
2. **Guard criteria ("Must NOT Have")** — boundaries the implementation must NOT cross:
   - Do not modify existing passing tests
   - Do not introduce stub/placeholder implementations (`return nil`, empty function bodies, `// TODO`)
   - Do not change API contracts or shared interfaces unless explicitly approved
3. **Verification criteria** — how completion is proven (specific test names, coverage thresholds, manual verification steps)

## Anti-Stub Clause

Code with empty function bodies, `return nil`, placeholder implementations, or trivially rewritten tests does NOT constitute completion. If full implementation is not feasible in one turn, explicitly report what was completed and what remains — never mark stubs as "done."

## Intermediate Checkpoints

For tasks estimated to take >30 min or touching >5 files:

- Report progress after every 3-5 files modified or after each major phase
- Each checkpoint: brief summary of what changed, what's next, any deviations from plan
- Commit at each checkpoint to maintain rollback points

## Completion Report

When finishing a non-trivial task, provide:

- What was done (list of changes)
- DoD items met (cross-reference against the defined criteria)
- What remains (if any — unfinished items, known limitations, follow-up tasks)

Skip standard checks for trivial single-file edits (typo fix, one-line change). Never remove completed history from `tasks/todo.md`.
